"But who is she? Who is she, Terry? She's new to all of us, and
                     the handsomest debutante of the season. Open the mysteries a little, old man;
                     and end our agonizing suspense."

"I must have that picture!" madame repeated, with a flash of the black eyes;
                     "sold or not, I still must have it. How do they call the artist?" She looked at
                     the catalogue. "'G. Locksley.' The name is new—is it not, Prince?"

"Really, Mr. Locksley is a charming companion," Lady Dynely was wont to say;
                     "talks better than any man I know. What a traveller he has been—been everywhere
                     and seen everything."

It was a short printed poem that told the story of the picture. Mechanically
                     she took it and read: 



"So close we are, and yet so far apart;

So close I feel your breath upon my cheek;

So far that all this love of mine is weak

To touch in any way your distant heart;

So close, that when I hear your voice I start

To see my whole life standing bare and bleak:

So far, that though for years and years I seek,

I shall not find thee other than thou art."

"I shall speak to the dear old dad to-morrow," he is saying ing. "Of course we
                     know what the answer will be. And I must get you an engagement ring. Let's see;
                     give me this little blue and white concern as a guide."

And "Mais oui monsieur," is the answer;
                     "there is one room at monsieur's service, but it is au
                        cinquième numéro quatre-vingts douze."

Yes, Terry was going to bring him to his senses—going to bring him to his wife;
                     and without a moment's hesitation, he hails a fiacre, gives the address, and is
                     whirled away through the noonday gaslit brilliance of the boulevards.

"Don't laugh at me," she returned, with a sudden flash of the black eyes;
                     "there's nothing to laugh at. I want to find a person who belongs to a
                     theatre—a lady, an actress. She plays at the Varieties."

"I told him nothing," Gordon answered, proudly, "only my name, and where I came
                     from, and how I got lost, and that I wanted to find you. "He said he knew you,
                     and would take me to you, and here I am."

"It is the most extraordinary thing I ever heard of," madame said, bewildered;
                     "and you are the most extraordinary child. Surely there is a Providence that
                     watches over children and fools."

France stoops and kisses her as a sister might, holding her close for a moment;
                     and a little sob she cannot wholly repress breaks from the poor, jealous child,
                     as she lays her head on France's breast.

"I beg your pardon, Terry," he says, more coherently than he has yet spoken;
                     "but this is a matter of no ordinary importance to me—a matter almost of life
                     and death."

Miss Forrester has recovered herself. Surprised excessively she is still;
                     intensely curious she is also, but outwardly she is only calmly, quietly
                     courteous.

Outside the gloomy and secluded mansion is wrapped in profound darkness;
                     inside, halls and passages are dimly lit—one room only, that in which M. Di
                     Venturini sits, being brightly illuminated.
